x4freetext: The experimental setup and procedures for data
The cyclotron at The Swedberg Lab.
The 98.5+-0.3 MeV protons from the cyclotron impinge
on the lithium target, producing neutrons with a full-
energy peak of 95.6+-0.5-MeV with a FWHM of 1.6-MeV.
The lithium target was 8-mm thick and enriched
resolution. Low-energy tail includes 13% of neutrons
Neutron flux is given on Fig.1 of J,PR/C,73,034611,2006
- detection of proton and light charged particles
(up to a=4) in the angular range 20-160 degrees
- array of eight Si-Si-CsI(Tl) telescopes placed in a
- particle identification using de-de and de-e
techniques. Two surface-barrier de silicon detectors
One Cs-I(Tl) e detector 50 mm long, 40 mm diameter
The colimated neutron beam has a diameter of 80
mm at the location of the target, where it is
monitored by a thin film breakdown counter.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Physical Review, Part C, Nuclear Physics, Vol.63, p.044001 (2001)

x4freetext: 1-mm thick polyethylene CH(2) target was used. The
disk of Si-O2 is used as the oxygen target.
- ratio of the events at main and parallel neutron
- the correction to 94-MeV is performed using the
known energy dependence of the Np-cross section.
- dead time of the data acquisition system
Calculations with GNASH and TALYS codes
individual points in the double-differential energy
spectra at 20-degree are typically 8% for protons, 13%
for deuterons, 20% for tritons, 15% for He-3 and 12%
The uncertainty in the absolute cross section is about
5%, which is due to uncertainties in (N-P) scattering
angle, contribution from the low-energy continuum of
the Li-7(P,N) spectrum to the Np-scattering proton
peak(3%), reference N,P cross section(2%), statistics
in the Np-scattering proton peak(2%), carbon
contribution(0.1%) and number of hydrogen nuclei(0.1%)
The error in collimator solid angle(1%-5%)
The error in number of oxygen nuclei-0.1%.
The error in CsI(Tl) intrinsic efficiency-1%.
The error in dead time is less than 0.1%.
The uncertainty is reported by authors in
Udomrat Tippawan and Stephan Pomp to approve.
